{"id":"2206.07061","submitter":"Fabio Bacchini","authors":"Fabio Bacchini, Lev Arzamasskiy, Vladimir Zhdankin, Gregory R. Werner,\n  Mitchell C. Begelman, Dmitri A. Uzdensky","title":"Fully kinetic shearing-box simulations of magnetorotational turbulence\n  in 2D and 3D. I. Pair plasmas","comments":"Submitted to ApJ","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3847/1538-4357/ac8a94","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE physics.plasm-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The magnetorotational instability (MRI) is a fundamental mechanism\ndetermining the macroscopic dynamics of astrophysical accretion disks. In\ncollisionless accretion flows around supermassive black holes, MRI-driven\nplasma turbulence cascading to microscopic (i.e. kinetic) scales can result in\nenhanced angular-momentum transport and redistribution, nonthermal particle\nacceleration, and a two-temperature state where electrons and ions are heated\nunequally. However, this microscopic physics cannot be captured with standard\nmagnetohydrodynamic (MHD) approaches typically employed to study the MRI. In\nthis work, we explore the nonlinear development of MRI turbulence in a pair\nplasma, employing fully kinetic Particle-in-Cell (PIC) simulations in two and\nthree dimensions. First, we thoroughly study the axisymmetric MRI with 2D\nsimulations, explaining how and why the 2D geometry produces results that\ndiffer substantially from MHD expectations. We then perform the largest (to\ndate) 3D simulations, for which we employ a novel shearing-box approach,\ndemonstrating that 3D PIC models can reproduce the mesoscale (i.e. MHD) MRI\ndynamics in sufficiently large runs. With our fully kinetic simulations, we are\nable to describe the nonthermal particle acceleration and angular-momentum\ntransport driven by the collisionless MRI. Since these microscopic processes\nultimately lead to the emission of potentially measurable radiation in\naccreting plasmas, our work is of prime importance to understand current and\nfuture observations from first principles, beyond the limitations imposed by\nfluid (MHD) models. While in this first study we focus on pair plasmas for\nsimplicity, our results represent an essential step toward designing more\nrealistic electron-ion simulations, on which we will focus in future work.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 14 Jun 2022 18:00:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-26"}
