{"id":"2206.07067","submitter":"Volker Karle","authors":"Volker Karle, Areg Ghazaryan and Mikhail Lemeshko","title":"Topological charges of periodically kicked molecules","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.130.103202","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall physics.atom-ph physics.chem-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We show that the simplest of existing molecules -- closed-shell diatomics not\ninteracting with one another -- host topological charges when driven by\nperiodic far-off-resonant laser pulses. A periodically kicked molecular rotor\ncan be mapped onto a ''crystalline'' lattice in angular momentum space. This\nallows to define quasimomenta and the band structure in the Floquet\nrepresentation, by analogy with the Bloch waves of solid-state physics.\nApplying laser pulses spaced by $1/3$ of the molecular rotational period\ncreates a lattice with three atoms per unit cell with staggered hopping. Within\nthe synthetic dimension of the laser strength, we discover Dirac cones with\ntopological charges. These Dirac cones, topologically protected by reflection\nand time-reversal symmetry, are reminiscent of (although not equivalent to)\nthat seen in graphene. They -- and the corresponding edge states -- are broadly\ntunable by adjusting the laser strength and can be observed in present-day\nexperiments by measuring molecular alignment and populations of rotational\nlevels. This paves the way to study controllable topological physics in\ngas-phase experiments with small molecules as well as to classify dynamical\nmolecular states by their topological invariants.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 14 Jun 2022 18:00:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 1 Jul 2022 12:24:55 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 2 Mar 2023 15:46:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-29"}
