alues of a-Si and show that they\nagree well with available experimental results from 10 K to room temperature.\nOur results also highlight the importance of quantum effects in the calculated\nthermal conductivity and support the quantum correction method based on the\nspectral thermal conductivity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 15 Jun 2022 15:36:22 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 20 Jun 2022 19:54:53 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 9 Jan 2023 12:11:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-22"}
{"id":"2206.07606","submitter":"Himangshu Prabal Goswami","authors":"Manash Jyoti Sarmah, Akanksha Bansal, and Himangshu Prabal Goswami","title":"Nonequilibrium fluctuations in boson transport through squeezed\n  reservoirs","comments":"6 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We explore the effects of quantum mechanical squeezing on the nonequilibrium\nfluctuations of bosonic transport between two squeezed harmonic reservoirs and\na two level system. A standard full counting statistics technique based on a\nquantum master equation is employed. We derive a nonzero thermodynamic affinity\nunder equal temperature setting of the two squeezed reservoirs. The odd\ncumulants are shown to be independent of squeezing under symmetric conditions,\nwhereas the even cumulants depend nonlinearly on the squeezing parameters. The\nodd and even cumulants saturate at two different but unique values which are\nidentified analytically. Further, squeezing always increases the magnitude of\nthe even cumulants in comparison to the unsqueezed case. We also recover a\nsteady state fluctuation theorem with squeezing dependent thermodynamic\naffinity and demonstrate the robustness of a steadystate thermodynamic\nuncertainty relationship.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 15 Jun 2022 15:37:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-16"}
